Creating a new user
command: sudo useradd joker
The sudo command gives you temporary superuser administrator privileges. If you run without using sudo, you get permission denied.
verification: sudo grep -w 'joker' /etc/passwd
Output: joker:x:1004:1004::/home/joker:/bin/sh
Explanation:(joker)- is the new user we have added
            (x)- password
            (1004:1004)- the userid and the groupid
            (/home/joker)- home directory
            (/bin/bash)- the default shell

Creating a user with home directory
Command: sudo useradd -m bob
(-m) tells the system to create a home directory for the user.
Verify: sudo ls -ld /home/bob
Output: drwxr-x--- 2 bob bob 4096 feb 17 17:16 /home/bob
Explanation:(d)- the directory
            (rwxr-x---) shows who can read, write, or execute in this directory
            (4096)- size of the directory in bytes
            (Feb 17 17:16)- when the directory was created

Setting a user password
Command: sudo passwd joker
You will be prompted to enter the password
Note:  Password will not be displayed as you type it; this is a security feature in Linux to prevent others from seeing your password as you type it
Linux stores encrypted passwords in a secure file called /etc/shadow.

Modifying user properties
Command: sudo usermod -d /home/wayne joker
(usermod)- modifies the user account settings
(-d /home/wayne)- specifies the new home directory
(joker)- the user we are modifying
verification: sudo grep -w 'joker' /etc/passwd
Output: joker:x:1004:1004::/home/wayne:/bin/bash

Changing user shell
Shell is a program that interprets and runs commands you type in the terminal. By default, the user "joker" is using /bin/bash as their shell,
While sh (Bourne shell) is a basic shell that is present on most unix-like system. bash (Bourne Again Shell) offers more features and is generally
more user-friendly
Changing from shell to bash
Command: sudo usermod -s /bin/bash joker
Verification: sudo grep -w 'joker' /etc/passwd
Output: joker:x:1004:1004::/home/wayne:/bin/bash

Add a user to a group
Linux uses groups to organise users and manage permissions
Command: sudo usermod -aG sudo joker
Verify: groups joker
Output: joker: joker sudo
To see the effect of the change: su - joker 
Output: You will be logged in as joker
Test: sudo cat /etc/shadow
Type exit to log out as joker

Locking and unlocking user accounts
1. To lock a user account command: sudo passwd -l joker
(-l) locks the account
Test: su - joker
You will be prompted for the Joker's password we created
Output: Authentication failure. Meaning the account is successfully locked
2. Unlocking the account
command: sudo passwd -u joker
Test: su - joker
Prompted the Joker's password the you logged in as joker. Typee exit to logout

Deleting a user
1. Deleting Bob and the home directory:
Command: sudo userdel -r bob
Verification: sudo grep -w 'bob' /etc/passwd
              sudo ls -ld /home/bob




